any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypertensive crisis","Low cerebrospinal fluid pressure headache","Meningitis","Neoplasm","Temporal arteritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Elow cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) pressure headache\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as a post-dural puncture headache. This type of headache is a common complication following a lumbar puncture and is characterised by a positional component, where the headache worsens when the patient is upright and improves when supine. The positional nature of the headache is due to changes in CSF pressure with posture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with a unilateral headache, often with scalp tenderness and jaw claudication, and is less likely in this scenario given the recent lumbar puncture and positional nature of the headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E can cause headaches, but these are usually not positional and would not be expected to present acutely following a lumbar puncture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertensive crisis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a severe headache, but it is not typically positional and would be associated with significantly elevated blood pressure readings, which are not mentioned in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause headache and neck stiffness, but the positional nature of the headache and the recent lumbar puncture make low CSF pressure headache more likely. Additionally, meningitis would present with other systemic symptoms such as fever and altered mental status.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Low cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) pressure headache, also known as post-dural puncture headache, is a common complication following a lumbar puncture.","The headache is typically positional, worsening when upright and improving when lying down.","Neck stiffness can accompany low CSF pressure headache due to meningeal irritation."],"references":["Bigal ME, Lipton RB. The differential diagnosis of chronic daily headaches: an algorithm-based approach. J Headache Pain. 2007 Oct;8(5):263-72. doi: 10.1007/s10194-007-0418-3. Epub 2007 Oct 23. PMID: 17955166; PMCID: PMC2793374","Ahmed F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. Br J Pain. 2012 Aug;6(3):124-32. doi: 10.1177/2049463712459691. PMID: 26516483; PMCID: PMC4590146","Spears RC. Low-pressure/spinal fluid leak headache. Curr Pain Headache Rep. 2014 Jun;18(6):425. doi: 10.1007/s11916-014-0425-4. PMID: 24760494.","Mehta D, Cheema S, Davagnanam I, Matharu M. Diagnosis and treatment evaluation in patients with spontaneous intracranial hypotension. Front Neurol. 2023 Mar 10;14:1145949. doi: 10.3389/fneur.2023.1145949. PMID: 36970531; PMCID: PMC10036855."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61878"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17217"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61878"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T09:48:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T09:49:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9907"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76369"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id